gaggle of begging calls at a rookery of 100-plus nests on and island in the middle of a suburban lagoon.  Interspersed are the calls of squabbling adults.  The rookery is host to Double-crested Cormorant, Anhinga, Snowy Egret and Common Gallinule as breeders.  Others regularly on the island in surrounding trees are Black-crowned Night-Heron, Wood Stork and both Black and Turkey Vulture.

The habitat on the rookery consists of scrubby trees on which nests of sticks are constructed, and higher grasses.  Most of the behavior centered around the nestlings begging for food.  Most of the nestlings are still in the down stage, although feathers are appearing.

file-name: XC161275-Great Egret among huge mixed flock -FL, Viera, Nov 19, 2013, 0916 AM.mp3
rmk:
A large collection of wading birds gathered at what remains of the temporarily drained sewage pond to feed on the concentrated fish.  Great Egrets were by far the noisiest in the crowded feeding flock.

The calling came from at least a few of the dozen Great Egrets present.  They called a lot in often somewhat aggressive interactions with neighboring Great Egrets.
